{
    "question_text": "<h3>Most Stones Removed with Same Row or Column</h3><p>On a 2D plane, we place <code>n</code> stones at some integer coordinate points. Each coordinate point may have at most one stone.</p><p>A stone can be removed if it shares either <b>the same row or the same column</b> as another stone that has not been removed.</p><p>Given an array <code>stones</code> of length <code>n</code> where <code>stones[i] = [x<sub>i</sub>, y<sub>i</sub>]</code> represents the location of the <code>i</code>-th stone, return the largest possible number of stones that can be removed.</p>",
    "difficulty": "MEDIUM",
    "marks": 10,
    "input_format": "The first line contains an integer `N`, the number of stones.\nThe next `N` lines each contain two space-separated integers `x_i` and `y_i`.",
    "output_format": "A single integer representing the maximum removable stones.",
    "constraints": [
        "1 <= stones.length <= 1000",
        "0 <= x_i, y_i <= 10^4",
        "No two stones are at the same coordinate point."
    ],
    "explanation": "This problem describes a collection of connected components in an undirected graph. We can imagine each stone as a node. Two stones share an edge if they have the same x-coordinate (row) or y-coordinate (col). Our goal is to find the maximum number of stones we can remove. A crucial observation is that for any connected component of `k` stones, we can always remove `k - 1` stones by sequentially taking away a stone that is connected to the remaining cluster. \nThus, the total number of removed stones equals the total number of stones minus the number of connected components. To easily track interconnected stones by row and column, we can use an efficient Union-Find (Disjoint Set) data structure, conceptually mapping the `y` coordinate uniquely to prevent overlaps with `x` coordinates by using `~y` or `y + 10001`.",
    "answer": "class DSU:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.p = {}\n        self.count = 0\n    def find(self, x):\n        if self.p.setdefault(x, x) != x:\n            self.p[x] = self.find(self.p[x])\n        return self.p[x]\n    def union(self, x, y):\n        px, py = self.find(x), self.find(y)\n        if px != py:\n            self.p[px] = py\n            self.count -= 1\n\ndef solve(stones):\n    dsu = DSU()\n    for x, y in stones:\n        dsu.find(x)\n        dsu.find(~y)\n        dsu.union(x, ~y)\n    dsu.count = len(dsu.p)\n    for x, y in stones:\n        dsu.union(x, ~y)\n    return len(stones) - dsu.count",
    "boilerplate": {
        "python": "import sys\n\ndef solve(points):\n    # User logic should be written here\n    return 0\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    input_data = sys.stdin.read().split()\n    if not input_data: sys.exit(0)\n    n = int(input_data[0])\n    points = []\n    idx = 1\n    for _ in range(n):\n        points.append([int(input_data[idx]), int(input_data[idx+1])])\n        idx += 2\n    print(solve(points))",
        "cpp": "#include <iostream>\n#include <vector>\nusing namespace std;\n\nint solve(vector<pair<int, int>>& points) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    if (cin >> n) {\n        vector<pair<int, int>> points(n);\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {\n            cin >> points[i].first >> points[i].second;\n        }\n        cout << solve(points) << endl;\n    }\n    return 0;\n}",
        "java": "import java.util.Scanner;\n\npublic class Main {\n    public static int solve(int[][] points) {\n        // User logic should be written here\n        return 0;\n    }\n\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);\n        if (sc.hasNextInt()) {\n            int n = sc.nextInt();\n            int[][] points = new int[n][2];\n            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n                points[i][0] = sc.nextInt();\n                points[i][1] = sc.nextInt();\n            }\n            System.out.println(solve(points));\n        }\n        sc.close();\n    }\n}",
        "javascript": "const fs = require('fs');\n\nfunction solve(points) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nconst input = fs.readFileSync(0, 'utf8').trim().split(/\\s+/);\nif (input.length > 0 && input[0] !== '') {\n    const n = parseInt(input[0]);\n    const points = [];\n    let idx = 1;\n    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n        points.push([parseInt(input[idx]), parseInt(input[idx+1])]);\n        idx += 2;\n    }\n    console.log(solve(points));\n}",
        "c": "#include <stdio.h>\n#include <stdlib.h>\n\nint solve(int n, int** points) {\n    // User logic should be written here\n    return 0;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    int n;\n    if (scanf(\"%d\", &n) == 1) {\n        int** points = (int**)malloc(n * sizeof(int*));\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {\n            points[i] = (int*)malloc(2 * sizeof(int));\n            scanf(\"%d %d\", &points[i][0], &points[i][1]);\n        }\n        printf(\"%d\\n\", solve(n, points));\n        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) free(points[i]);\n        free(points);\n    }\n    return 0;\n}"
